review_blob: Wow, this is nice. Absolutely perfect mouthfeel and carbonation, pure velvet. A bit of a smokey smell, whisky, tiny bit of booze. Lots of chocolate in the taste mixed with smoke and whisky again, lovely combo. This is good drinking.

The only thing that smells this much like Jack Daniels is Jack Daniels. Quite high level of carbonation.The taste of malts, wood, vanilla, quite bitter with a touch of sweetness all work very well together. Somthing like a little bit of ash in there as well, nice. Drinkable and delicious.
beer_name: Emelisse White Label Barley Wine (Jack Daniels BA)

review_blob: Sweet, malts, not a lot of bitterness or hops. Bit of banana and cloves, not as much as some other tripels. A big smell and taste of bubble gum. Nice to have one of every once in a while, but not more than one in a session.
Way better than the normal kriek. Sour with cherry aroma and taste, not artificial like the kriek. Little bit of funk going on. Very drinkable, great with cheese.
Quite a lot like the normal oude geuze. A bit less sour, a bit more balanced out, but a lot more bitter. Again that harsh after taste. Still, very enjoyable.
Quite bitter, lots of funk, amazing amounts of wood. Bit of citrus in there as well. A kind of harsh bitter after taste that doesnt change the drinkability for the better. Still good beer though.
Enjoyable, lots of cherries, but a bit artificial. Taste really sweetened, like candy. A nice beer, but Id rather have a real unsweetened kriek.
Way better than the normal kriek. Quit sour, not too sweet, lots of raspberries and some nice funk. Good beer and very drinkable.
Ok beer. Yeast and bread, bit of caramel, bit of roast in there. Not too sweet. Ok, just nothing special. Dont really feel the need to have it again.
This was not really my thing. Spices, mostly peppery. Bit of malts, but not enough to balance out the bitterness. Not a lot of hops aromas, just pure bitterness, meh.
Typical vlaams bruin. Dark sugar (not a lot), sour, wood and fruity notes, mainly cherry. Easy to drink, but there are better examples of the style out there.

Good beer, all the flavours there, that one would associate with an imperial stout, coffee chocolate, roast. Hoppier than most stouts though. Got a bottle to age, will try after some while. Would have this more often for sure if it werent so hard to come by.
Amber, very hoppy, with a lot of sweetness from malts to balance. Still on the sweet side of things, with the alcohol content showing and adding to the sweetness.
Hoppy, bitter, enough malts to balance. Easy drinking. Wont go out of my way to search it out, but if it crosses my path again by chance, I wont hesitate to try again.
Watery, bit of caramel, sweet. Notes of the taste of the bavaria pilsener coming through. Its ok, but definitely nothing more than that.

Sweet, alcoholic. Awfull, this is fuel, not beer. Saw the gold on sale today at the supermarket, maybe Ill buy it for the tock, but are really reluctant to do so, because of the awfull experience that was this version.
Sweet with dark sugar. Sour, but not mindblowing. Bit of wood, fruity. Fairly easy drinking. Straightforward vlaams bruin.
Hops and coffee, body not too light, not too heavy. Very drinkable. Readily available and a regular of mine.
In the aroma a lot of bourbon and vanilla, almost to the point it smells like coconut. Taste is of wood and bourbon with the notes of the base gonzo shining through, mostly coffee. Very nice.
beer_name: Flying Dog Wild Dog Barrel-Aged Gonzo

review_blob: Lovely pine and fruity armoa and taste. Bitter but balanced. Really drinkable, very easy to drink a lot of. A regular.
beer_name: Flying Dog Snake Dog IPA (2008 and later)

review_blob: Sweet, malts, balanced by a bit of hops. Works for me, quite enjoyable. Just a little bit of the alcohol noticeable, warming.
These spiced beers are not for me, I can take one but usually dont want to drink more than one. Spiced quite a bit. Sweetness as well.
beer_name: Anchor Our Special Ale (2005 and later)

review_blob: Average macro. Bit darker than the other pilseners. Taste is much the same, nothing special. It gets you drunk.
Sweet, cardboard, malts, alcohol. Not nice, cant really think of a reason why I would buy this again.
Pretty much one of the best supermarket bocks. Roast, caramel, sweet. Bit syrupy mouthfeel.
Average pilsener, nothing special, nothing standing out. Quite indistinguishable from other macros. Why not drink something nicer?
Not too sweet, which I like in an ipa. Hops standing out, very nice smell; taste as well. Easy to drink, bottle was gone in the blink of an eye. Straightforward, but very enjoyable.
Body a bit heavier than Frederiksen, which is good. Still very drinkable though. Nice roast coming through. Very complex with added notes of vanilla besides the roasty coffee flavours.
Mouthfeel even a bit lighter than the normal version. Very full of flavour, all of the base is still there but with added port notes. Port wine, wood, sugar. I like port, this is delicious.

Still not very heavy for an imperial stout. Very full of flavour though, while still being easy to drink. Bit of vanilla going on besides teh obvious chocolate and coffee. Hops peaking through as well.
Quite light mouthfeel, notes of coffee and roast. Very easy to drink. Good balance between being full of flavour and still being easy to drink.
Holy smoke! Couldnt think of an expression more appropriate. Very smokey and peaty, like a big piece of bacon is being slapped in you face, delicious.
Nothing like a stout really, but I dont care. Very wine like, with oak and tannins coming through. Mouthfeel is light, but it sort of fits. really drinkable, bottle went down really fast.
beer_name: Alvinne Podge Bourgogne Barrel Oak Aged

review_blob: Yeast, bread. A bit sour, balancing, not overpowering. Not enough chocolate of coffee of roast to make this a stand out stout. Mouthfeel a bit too light as well.
A bit sour and lots of sweetness, not enough to hide the alcohol though. Too much alcohol showing te be nice and drinkable. Malts and caramel, fruity.
Acidic, a bit fruity. Too much lactic sourness for me. Nice to have tried though, interesting, but not that great.
Light hops, grains, malty caramel with a bit of caramel. Wouldnt have thought this is a bock. Noy that noce to drink a lot of, kind of on the sweet side.
Lots of yeast inn the pour, yeast in the taste as well. Expected more hops from this. Not really all that hoppy or bitter, there are better examples of hoppy belgian beers than this.
Lots of sediment in the pour. Very sweet and alcohol really coming through. Bit of spices in the taste. Ok beer, nothing special.
Muddy pour. Lots of spices in the smell and taste as well. A bit of chocolate and liquorice. Too much spice for me to really enjoy, but a fun experience.
Weird stuff; malty, spicy. Complex but not well integrated. Nice to have tried, but definitely wont pick it up again.

A bit disappointed, perhaps I need a rerate. Theres coffee there but not mindblowing amounts. Other flavours are all of a decent stout, a good stout even, but not great. Very easy to drink for its alcohol percentage.
Yuck smell and taste of sulfur and cardboard. I pray I wont ever have to drink this again.

Sweet and watery, not much unlike all of the other macros really, wouldnt be able to pick this out in a blind tasting. It does its job, which is getting you drunk without hurting your wallet too much.
Sweetness and alcohol, not my thing. Definitely wont have this again, there are a lot of beer Id rather drink.
Looks amazing. Watery, drinkable, not that much flavour, bit of coffee, bit of roast. Nice and easy going; can drink a lot of this stuff.

Smell of wet cardboard with a bit of roast and coffee. Watery and thin, but very very drinkable. Again that bit of cardboard in the taste, nicely bitter taste. Nice session beer and much like guinness, but a bit better.

Amazing smell loaded with fresh fruity hops. taste is mainly bitter, but nicely balanced with a bit of sweetness and caramel. This caramel flavour detracts a bit from the hops I think, would have been better if it was more straightforward and a bit lighter.

Not a big fan of the spiced beers, but this is pretty ok. Lots of spices coming through; nutmeg, cloves, cinnamon. Balanced and not overpowering, the spices are adding to the flavour not completely taking away everything else.

easily the best chouffe. Banana, bread, yeast, malts; all covered in a load of hop aroma and flavour. The hops are the first thing to hit you and then the other flavours enter. Not a perfect blend of styles, but enjoyable.
